{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"coaching":[],"coverage":{"counts":{"advisory_overflow":0,"advisory_surfaced":0,"blocking":0,"dropped":0,"indeterminate":21},"det":{"P1":{"ac_items":12,"blocking":false,"clarity_score":7,"name":"readiness-shape","ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P2":{"blocking":false,"name":"resolution","ran":true,"references":0,"resolved":0,"status":"pass"},"P3":{"blocking":false,"name":"package-existence","packages":0,"ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P4":{"ac_items":12,"blocking":false,"desc_chars":12914,"file_impact":8,"name":"oversize","ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P5":{"blocking":false,"children":3,"edges":3,"name":"task-dag","ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P6":{"ac_items":12,"blocking":false,"name":"ac-quality","ran":true,"status":"pass","verify_commands_linted":4,"verify_lint_abstained":4},"P7":{"blocking":false,"destructive_hits":[],"name":"destructive-sniff","ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P8":{"blocking":false,"budget_tokens":868000,"name":"reviewability","plan_tokens":3245,"ran":true,"status":"pass","worst_parent_child_pair_tokens":5315},"P9":{"applicable":false,"blocking":false,"file_impact":8,"name":"file-impact-coverage","ran":true,"status":"pass"}},"llm_ran":true,"metrics":{"claim_path":"no-llm/no-network (structural; the fast claim check is a local HMAC verify)","det_ms":312.9,"llm_calls":22,"llm_ms":954846.5,"total_ms":955286.2,"verify_requests":46},"remediation":{"baseline":"signature","eligible":true,"reasons":{"code_unchanged":true,"plan_changed":true,"prior_sidecar":true,"registry_unchanged":true,"signed":true,"within_window":true}},"routing":{"agent_tier":["G3","G4","G6","T1","T10","T11","T13","T14","T3","T5c","T8"],"single_turn":["COH","E1","E2","E3","F1","F4","G5","T12","T2","T4","T5e","T7"]}},"findings":[{"block_threshold":0.6,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Split AC6 into at minimum two separate checkboxes: one for schema/generated-type correctness (test_schema_ticket_state.py, test_schema_outputs.py, gen_types --check) and one for runtime output-surface exposure (test_creation_channel.py -k projections, test_export_ndjson.py).","cohort":["E2","F1"],"criteria":["F1"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["'TicketState schemas, generated types, runtime show/list/search projections, plus exported NDJSON expose the six-value enum with a const-true optional inference marker.'","Proof command chains four independent test modules: test_creation_channel.py -k projections, test_schema_ticket_state.py, test_schema_outputs.py, test_export_ndjson.py, plus python -m rebar.schemas.gen_types --check","Rubric: 'a coherent single-outcome deliverable — not an epic-of-epics'"],"finding":"AC6 bundles four distinct observable outcomes — JSON schema files, generated TypeScript/typed-surface output, runtime show/list/search projections, and NDJSON export — into a single acceptance-criterion checkbox with a compound proof command. An executor who delivers three of the four sub-outcomes has no clear signal that the criterion is unmet.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fbec6a7839a259600","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Acceptance Criteria — AC6 ('TicketState schemas, generated types, runtime show/list/search projections, plus exported NDJSON expose the six-value enum…')","norm_id":"n8a5e4fd12551bff4","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["An implementer ships schema changes and generated types but defers runtime projection wiring; the compound AC appears green in CI if the projection test file is not yet created, masking the gap.","A reviewer cannot tell from the single checkbox which of the four sub-outcomes remains incomplete if the compound test command partially fails."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Replace the single AC6 checkbox with:\n- [ ] JSON schemas (ticket_state.schema.json, output schemas) and generated types expose the six-value creation_channel enum and the const-true inference marker. Prove with: uv run pytest -q tests/interfaces/contracts/test_schema_ticket_state.py tests/interfaces/contracts/test_schema_outputs.py && python -m rebar.schemas.gen_types --check.\n- [ ] Runtime show/list/search projections and exported NDJSON surface creation_channel (and creation_channel_inferred where applicable) from compiled state. Prove with: uv run pytest -q tests/interfaces/facades/test_creation_channel.py -k projections tests/interfaces/io/test_export_ndjson.py.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add an Acceptance Criterion that sends a mutation event (e.g. a status-change or tag-update) containing a `creation_channel` key through the reducer and asserts the compiled_state `creation_channel` is unchanged, proving reducer-level immutability enforcement.","cohort":["COH","E1"],"criteria":["E1"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["'Reducer processors treat creation_channel as CREATE/SNAPSHOT-only state and ignore the key on every later mutation event, enforcing immutability below individual writers.'","No AC test command exercises a mutation event that includes a creation_channel key and asserts the compiled_state value is unchanged."],"finding":"The Architecture section specifies 'Reducer processors treat creation_channel as CREATE/SNAPSHOT-only state and ignore the key on every later mutation event, enforcing immutability below individual writers,' but no Acceptance Criterion directly verifies this reducer-level enforcement. AC3 tests outbound Jira at the interface level, and AC6/AC7 test compaction durability — neither proves that a raw mutation event (PUT, STATUS_CHANGE, etc.) carrying a creation_channel key cannot alter the reduced value.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f81dd8c985cb3a644","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Architecture Decisions section (immutability paragraph); Acceptance Criteria section (no covering AC)","norm_id":"n0d80407bfb4e9f40","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["An implementer adds reducer logic but accidentally lets a PATCH/PUT event overwrite the field; no AC catches the regression.","A future mutation event type is introduced and inherits incorrect reducer handling; the gap is invisible until an audit surfaces wrong channel attribution."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Append an AC such as: 'A mutation event carrying a creation_channel key does not alter the compiled creation_channel. Prove with uv run pytest -q tests/unit/reducer/test_creation_channel_immutability.py -k mutation_ignored.'","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Extend AC9 to require that docs/event-schema.md (or docs/output-schemas.md) explicitly documents the diagnostic trust boundary of `creation_channel_inferred` (i.e., that it is diagnostic metadata, not a security attestation), matching Success Criteria item 5.","cohort":["COH","E1"],"criteria":["E1"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Success Criteria: 'The public schema and documentation define the vocabulary, default/fallback semantics, import behavior, and diagnostic trust boundary.'","AC9: 'docs/event-schema.md plus docs/output-schemas.md define CREATE/SNAPSHOT placement, the enum, Jira inference, import semantics, plus the distinction from actor/environment/source_* provenance.'","Architecture: 'It is diagnostic metadata, not a security attestation.' — this trust boundary statement has no corresponding documentation requirement in AC9."],"finding":"Success Criteria item 5 requires that 'The public schema and documentation define the vocabulary, default/fallback semantics, import behavior, and diagnostic trust boundary,' but AC9 lists only 'CREATE/SNAPSHOT placement, the enum, Jira inference, import semantics, plus the distinction from actor/environment/source_* provenance' as the required documentation content — omitting the diagnostic trust boundary (i.e., the documented statement that creation_channel_inferred is diagnostic metadata, not a security attestation).","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f4dd9cabcc0276962","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Success Criteria item 5; Acceptance Criteria AC9 (docs/event-schema.md and docs/output-schemas.md)","norm_id":"n8aaa52705d1b3465","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["Downstream consumers rely on creation_channel_inferred as a security control; without documented trust semantics the field's limitations are invisible until misused.","An auditor tool treats inferred attribution as authoritative; the diagnostic-only caveat is undiscoverable from the published schema."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Add 'plus the diagnostic trust boundary of creation_channel_inferred (diagnostic metadata, not a security attestation)' to the AC9 documentation content list.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Differentiate AC7 and AC8 by either giving AC8 a -k filter that excludes AC7's scenarios or by collapsing both into a single AC with a clear explanation of which story each test group belongs to.","cohort":["COH","E1"],"criteria":["E1"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["AC7: 'uv run pytest -q tests/interfaces/lifecycle/test_creation_channel_compaction.py -k \"recorded or inferred or rollback_recovery\"'","AC8: 'uv run pytest -q tests/interfaces/lifecycle/test_creation_channel_compaction.py tests/scripts/reducer/test_reducer_snapshot.py' (no -k filter)"],"finding":"AC7 and AC8 both invoke `tests/interfaces/lifecycle/test_creation_channel_compaction.py`; AC8 applies no -k filter to that file, meaning it runs all tests in the file including the 'recorded or inferred or rollback_recovery' subset already mandated by AC7. The AC7 scenarios are thus fully subsumed by AC8 for that file, creating redundant verification steps without adding clarity about which story each belongs to.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f5b2da49ca6e5b17d","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Acceptance Criteria AC7 and AC8","norm_id":"n3c93e5557ed6d485","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["A reviewer checking AC7 completion cannot tell which scenarios it uniquely owns versus those covered by AC8's broader run, making story-level sign-off ambiguous.","If the compaction test file is refactored, the duplication could mask which AC each test is meant to satisfy."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add a persisted ADR (e.g., `docs/adr/creation-channel-provenance.md`) or extend `CLAUDE.md` to capture the closed-vocabulary design rationale, the three-signal historical inference predicate and its constants, the 'no writer-only mode' decision, and the downgrade compaction-pause matrix — so future contributors can extend the system without hunting down this ticket.","cohort":["T2","T5e"],"criteria":["T5e"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan specifies updates to docs/event-schema.md, docs/output-schemas.md, and docs/concurrency.md, but no ADR or CLAUDE.md update is listed anywhere in the plan.","The rationale for the closed enum, the exact three-signal inference predicate (LEGACY_JIRA_AUTHOR, LEGACY_JIRA_ENV_ID, ticket_id prefix), the 'no writer-only binary mode' decision, and the downgrade compaction-pause requirement are design decisions that future maintainers or contributors must understand to safely extend the system — but they exist only in this ticket.","'A future ingress such as a GitHub reconciler extends the closed vocabulary deliberately.' — this extension contract needs a durable home in the repo, not just the ticket narrative."],"finding":"The plan introduces a novel immutable audit dimension with a closed vocabulary, a historical inference predicate with specific signal constants, and a downgrade/compaction recovery matrix — architectural decisions captured only in this ticket, not in a persisted ADR or CLAUDE.md update in the repository.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"ffa46ee864f19a150","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Architecture Decisions section; Scope/OUT; Risks and Mitigations; AC lines referencing docs/event-schema.md, docs/output-schemas.md, docs/concurrency.md","norm_id":"n1c4b16a384730936","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["A contributor adding a new ingress (e.g., GitHub reconciler) six months from now has no in-repo design doc explaining the closed-vocab contract or why the three-signal predicate was chosen, leading to ad-hoc vocabulary extension or incorrect inference predicates.","A new engineer asked to change the downgrade procedure must reconstruct the rationale from git log / ticket history rather than a maintained design document."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Create docs/adr/creation-channel-provenance.md covering: (1) why the vocab is closed and how to extend it, (2) the exact three-signal Jira inference predicate and its false-positive controls, (3) the 'no configuration switch / no intermediate binary mode' decision and its tradeoff, (4) the downgrade three-state matrix and the compaction-pause requirement. Reference it from the existing docs/event-schema.md and docs/concurrency.md updates already in scope.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add a lightweight deployment gate (e.g., an env-var flag `REBAR_CREATION_CHANNEL_ENABLED=true/false` that defaults the field to `unknown` when false, or a canary step in the rollout runbook) so attribution writes can be enabled incrementally and disabled without a full binary rollback.","cohort":["E3","T12"],"criteria":["T12"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["'The MVP deliberately has no writer-only configuration switch or intermediate binary mode; attribution defects are recovered by pausing the affected creation ingress at the deployment boundary and rolling forward.'","No flag/canary/staged-rollout mechanism is described anywhere in the plan."],"finding":"The plan explicitly forgoes any feature flag, canary, or staged rollout ('The MVP deliberately has no writer-only configuration switch or intermediate binary mode'), meaning the behavior change (writing creation_channel on every CREATE) reaches all production traffic in a single binary flip with no partial-exposure path.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f802bb2b6a4c6755f","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Architecture Decisions — 'The public change is additive… The MVP deliberately has no writer-only configuration switch or intermediate binary mode.'","norm_id":"n1e4ae562d1b6e5bd","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["A latent bug in the creation_channel writer path (e.g., wrong channel assigned to MCP or Jira inbound) immediately affects 100% of CREATE traffic; there is no flag to turn off new writes while preserving the read path.","If the Jira reconciler is a long-running service, it begins writing jira channels immediately on deploy with no option to soft-launch or validate in shadow mode first."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Introduce a single env-var guard (e.g., `REBAR_CREATION_CHANNEL_ENABLED`) read at writer-boundary entry; when false, the channel defaults to `unknown` (identical to the historical fallback). Document the flag in the rollout section and add an AC for it. This preserves the additive contract while providing a cheap kill-switch without data cleanup.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Specify an automated or semi-automated mechanism to enforce the compaction pause during downgrade (e.g., a schema-version check in the compactor that refuses to run against new-format events when the binary lacks the field, or a `--creation-channel-epoch` flag that compaction checks), and document a tooling-assisted way to identify affected IDs without manual log scanning.","cohort":["E3","T12"],"criteria":["T12"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["'before a full binary downgrade, stop every rebar compact invocation… If that pause is violated, record affected IDs from the downgrade-window compaction activity, re-deploy the new binary, and rebuild those snapshots from the full log with rebuild_snapshot_from_full_log/include_retired'","No automated mechanism for detecting or enforcing the compaction pause (e.g., a compaction lock, a schema-version guard in the compactor, or a runbook-enforced gate) is described.","'record affected IDs from the downgrade-window compaction activity' implies a manual audit step with no tooling."],"finding":"The rollback path requires a precondition (stopping all rebar compact invocations before the downgrade) that is not 'cheap' or self-enforcing: if that pause is violated, recovery requires identifying all affected ticket IDs from the downgrade-window compaction activity and running rebuild_snapshot_from_full_log on each — an operationally expensive compensating step with no automated tooling described.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f3e40e43312dd3bcd","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Architecture Decisions — rollback matrix; Risks and Mitigations — 'Snapshot omission/recovery'; AC — Story 568c regression.","norm_id":"n8fec1e213554e2e9","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["A rapid incident rollback skips the compaction-pause step; the old compactor runs during the downgrade window and produces SNAPSHOTs without creation_channel; on re-upgrade, the field is silently missing for those tickets until an operator manually identifies and rebuilds them.","In environments with continuous or scheduled compaction (cron, daemon), the pause is easy to forget or incomplete."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.6,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Clarify how `create_core`'s new `creation_channel` parameter handles out-of-scope callers (Jira direct writer, import path) during the 6fe2→e622 transition: either give the parameter a temporary default (e.g., `python`) for unclaimed callers in 6fe2 and document that e622 replaces it, or expand 6fe2's scope to stub all callers with a sensible value so each story remains independently deployable.","cohort":["G6"],"criteria":["G6"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["'Make composer.create_core require an internal keyword-only concrete channel' (6fe2 What)","'OUT: Jira inbound creation, NDJSON import ... Those are assigned to later children' (6fe2 Scope)","import_ndjson.py line 229: `local = create_ticket(repo_root=rr, **_provenance.create_kwargs(rec))` — this calls rebar.create_ticket → composer.create_core, which would be required to accept creation_channel by 6fe2","The stories 'run sequentially through depends_on links' but a required-parameter change on create_core breaks all callers simultaneously"],"finding":"Story 6fe2 plans to make `creation_channel` a required keyword-only parameter on `create_core`, but the import path (`import_ndjson.import_tickets` → `rebar.create_ticket` → `composer.create_core`) goes through `create_core` and is explicitly OUT of scope for 6fe2 (assigned to e622). If the parameter is required with no default in 6fe2, the import call site breaks in the 6fe2→e622 deployment window. The plan is silent on how `create_core` callers that are not yet updated are handled between stories.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f2cb7955cf4503644","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Architecture Decisions / Decomposition and Sequencing; story 6fe2 Scope (OUT: NDJSON import); story e622 Scope (IN: NDJSON import)","norm_id":"nd891759eca5561bf","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["After story 6fe2 lands and before e622 lands, any invocation of `rebar import` (NDJSON) would raise a TypeError because `create_core` requires `creation_channel` but `rebar.create_ticket` does not yet pass it.","A CI run that exercises the import path against the 6fe2 branch without e622 would fail with a missing-argument error, undermining the claim that stories deliver 'independently testable audit increments'."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"In story 6fe2, give `creation_channel` a default of `\"python\"` in `create_core` (documented as a temporary default for unclaimed callers) and add a NOTE that e622 replaces each out-of-scope call site with the correct channel. Alternatively, expand 6fe2's scope to add stub `creation_channel` arguments to all `create_core` callers so the codebase compiles cleanly after 6fe2 alone.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add an explicit declarative assertion of the intermediate post-rollback schema state in docs/concurrency.md (and mirrored in the Architecture Decisions rollback matrix): 'After a full binary downgrade + compaction pause violation, affected SNAPSHOTs have creation_channel absent from compiled_state while the corresponding .retired CREATE retains the field — this is an incorrect-but-recoverable state detectable by fsck; no data is destroyed.' This assertion should be testable by the fsck --repair-snapshots regression in story 568c.","cohort":["T11"],"criteria":["T11"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["'a first old-code compaction omits the field from its SNAPSHOT, but the creation-bearing CREATE remains permanently retained as .retired' — this describes a state but does not formally assert it as the declared schema state after rollback","'If that pause is violated, record affected IDs from the downgrade-window compaction activity, re-deploy the new binary, and rebuild those snapshots' — this is a recovery procedure, not a schema-state assertion","T11 criterion: 'the plan must assert on the schema STATE AFTER rollback, not merely that rollback exits 0'","The three-state matrix in the Architecture Decisions section is qualitatively described but the intermediate post-rollback, pre-recovery schema state (SNAPSHOT missing creation_channel, compiled_state incomplete) is not declared as a formally incorrect-but-recoverable state with a testable assertion"],"finding":"The plan describes the post-rollback recovery procedure (stop compaction, re-deploy, rebuild from .retired CREATEs) but does not explicitly assert the schema STATE of affected SNAPSHOTs in the intermediate window between a full binary downgrade with compaction pause violation and the completion of the compensating-forward rebuild. Auditors and operators cannot verify whether the intermediate state is 'field absent but recoverable' or 'silently incorrect' without an explicit assertion.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f66017dc2f084483f","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Architecture Decisions — rollback matrix paragraph; Risks and Mitigations — 'Downgrade first-compaction omission'; AC — 'docs/concurrency.md defines the full-downgrade three-state schema matrix'","norm_id":"n071b9e10a5ae825a","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["An operator performs a full binary downgrade and the compaction pause is violated; the resulting SNAPSHOTs are missing creation_channel in compiled_state. Without an explicit schema-state assertion, operators cannot programmatically verify the intermediate state before running recovery — they must infer it from the procedure description.","A future fsck check needs to detect 'SNAPSHOT missing creation_channel where retained .retired CREATE has it' — this detection logic is mentioned (story 568c, fsck --repair-snapshots) but the declared schema state that triggers it is not formally pinned in the plan."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"In docs/concurrency.md's three-state matrix, add a fourth row or sub-point: 'Intermediate post-violation state (pre-recovery): SNAPSHOT.data.compiled_state lacks creation_channel; .retired CREATE file retains creation_channel. State is incorrect-but-recoverable. fsck detects this via the existing --repair-snapshots seam. No data is destroyed.' Then extend the story 568c fsck regression to assert this intermediate state explicitly before running the rebuild.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add gen_types.py to story 6fe2's Files section and specify that _pytype() must handle the 'const' keyword, emitting `Literal[<const_value>]` (e.g. `Literal[True]`) so {\"const\": true} renders as `Literal[True]` rather than `Any`.","cohort":["T8"],"criteria":["T8"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan: 'Encode the marker as {\"const\": true}; recorded and unknown projections omit it. Regenerate derived public types'","gen_types.py _pytype(): handles $ref, enum (inline), array, object, typed scalars — no 'const' branch","gen_types.py line 146-148: `if jtype is None: self._used_typing.add('Any'); return 'Any'` — hit when schema node is {\"const\": true} (has no 'type')","gen_types.py is absent from story 6fe2 Files section: no implementer is explicitly tasked with adding const handling","plan: 'Prove with ... python -m rebar.schemas.gen_types --check' — the check would pass but produce an incorrect 'Any' type"],"finding":"gen_types.py cannot correctly render creation_channel_inferred: the plan specifies encoding the inference marker as {\"const\": true} in ticket_state.schema.json and states that 'Regenerate derived public types' will produce correct types, but the existing _pytype() method in gen_types.py has no handler for the 'const' keyword — a {\"const\": true} node has no 'type', 'enum', or '$ref', so it falls to the `if jtype is None` branch (line 146-148) and renders as 'Any' rather than 'Literal[True]'. The plan does not list gen_types.py in any story's Files section, so this gap would go undetected until the drift-gate fires.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f33c69e954c808f16","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Architecture Decisions (parent plan) + story 6fe2-ab22-c231-4a41 Files section; src/rebar/schemas/gen_types.py lines 115-148","norm_id":"n51a3b72d933dcbea","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["An implementer adds {\"const\": true} to ticket_state.schema.json, runs gen_types, and gets creation_channel_inferred: NotRequired[Any] instead of NotRequired[Literal[True]], silently violating the typed contract","The drift-gate CI check passes (file is regenerated correctly from the generator's perspective) but the generated type is semantically wrong"],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"In gen_types.py _pytype(), add a branch before the `jtype = node.get('type')` line: `if 'const' in node: self._used_typing.add('Literal'); return f'Literal[{repr(node[\"const\"])}]'`. Add gen_types.py to story 6fe2's Files section.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Specify validate_creation_channel()'s interface: the exact exception type it raises (e.g. ValueError), the error message format, whether 'unknown' is rejected inside the validator or by each caller, and how the Jira inbound seam (apply_inbound_records.py) handles that exception.","cohort":["T8"],"criteria":["T8"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan: 'Every live producer declares its channel at its entry boundary. Local create_core callers plus the direct Jira CREATE seam use the shared runtime validator before writing'","Plan: 'Add the matching runtime constant plus validate_creation_channel(...) helper to src/rebar/reducer/_version.py' — no return type, exception type, or error message specified","Plan: 'unknown is reserved for historical compatibility and is rejected for new live writes' — stated only in 6fe2 Approach Rationale prose, not in the validator spec","apply_inbound_records.py does not use CommandError; its error path is different from composer.py","No specification of what happens when apply_inbound_records calls validate_creation_channel with an invalid value: does it raise ValueError? RuntimeError? Log and continue?"],"finding":"The write-rejection rule for 'unknown' on live new writes is not co-located with the validate_creation_channel specification: the plan names a shared validate_creation_channel() helper in reducer/_version.py but does not specify its interface — what it returns, what exception it raises, or whether 'unknown' rejection is inside the validator or in each caller. Separately, the direct Jira CREATE seam (apply_inbound_records.py) uses a different error-handling path than CommandError, and the plan does not specify what validate_creation_channel raises in that context.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f8658a181794a4a6e","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Architecture Decisions: 'create_core callers plus the direct Jira CREATE seam use the shared runtime validator before writing'; story 6fe2-ab22-c231-4a41 What section: 'validate_creation_channel(...) helper'","norm_id":"nd7579a7392292fc7","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["One implementer puts the unknown-rejection guard inside validate_creation_channel (raising ValueError); another puts it in each caller site — different behavior when the validator is called from the Jira seam vs. create_core","The Jira inbound seam catches all exceptions best-effort (as _ensure_inbound_assignee_identity does) and the validator failure is silently swallowed, allowing an invalid channel to persist"],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Clarify in story 568c whether _project_legacy_creation_channel is placed inside process_snapshot() (mirroring the managed_refs/attestations/keyring migration pattern) or at another call site, and specify separately where it is called during full-log CREATE projection in e622.","cohort":["T8"],"criteria":["T8"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["568c What: 'After process_snapshot restores compiled_state, call _project_legacy_creation_channel(state), the state-shaped helper supplied by e622'","e622 What: 'Add _project_legacy_creation_channel(state: dict) -> None in reducer/_processors.py. It is a no-op when state already has creation_channel; otherwise it reads state[\"ticket_id\"], state.get(\"author\"), plus state.get(\"env_id\") ... This state-shaped interface is shared unchanged by post-CREATE projection here and post-SNAPSHOT restore in child 568c'","process_snapshot() in _processors.py: all existing migration hooks are placed INSIDE the function (managed_refs guard at line 763, attestations guard at line 772, keyring guard at line 787)","The plan does not explicitly say 'add this call inside process_snapshot' nor 'call it from the dispatch layer'"],"finding":"_project_legacy_creation_channel's call site within process_snapshot is ambiguous: the plan (story 568c) says 'After process_snapshot restores compiled_state, call _project_legacy_creation_channel(state)' but does not specify whether this call is placed INSIDE process_snapshot() itself (as an additional step at the end) or OUTSIDE it at the replay-loop dispatch point in _replay.py. The two placements differ: inside process_snapshot, the call runs only when a SNAPSHOT event is processed; at the dispatch level, it could be applied more broadly. The existing migration hooks (managed_refs, attestations, keyring) are ALL placed inside process_snapshot — but the plan describes _project_legacy_creation_channel as a 'state-shaped interface shared unchanged by post-CREATE projection here and post-SNAPSHOT restore', implying it must also be callable from CREATE projection, which further blurs the placement.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f8d511d6b65c44737","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Story 568c-b44b-7e2b-4d87 What section: 'After process_snapshot restores compiled_state, call _project_legacy_creation_channel(state)'; Architecture Decisions (parent plan): 'Reducer processors treat creation_channel as CREATE/SNAPSHOT-only state'","norm_id":"n2a4d15eee783e204","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["Implementer places the call inside process_snapshot; SNAPSHOT-only replay works correctly but CREATE-path projection does not call it (separate call needed in process_create)","Implementer places the call at the replay-loop level; it is called after every event type, not just SNAPSHOT — producing unexpected behavior for non-SNAPSHOT events"],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Following the established pattern, place the call at the end of process_snapshot() (mirroring the managed_refs guard) with the same guard structure: `if 'creation_channel' not in compiled_state: _project_legacy_creation_channel(state)`. For e622's CREATE path, call it at the end of process_create after folding all CREATE data fields.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Extend e622's helper tests or 568c's SNAPSHOT tests to cover SNAPSHOT-specific edge cases for _project_legacy_creation_channel (explicitly-None creation_channel, unexpected-value passthrough), and resolve the scope-OUT contradiction in e622 by documenting that the helper's design intentionally supports both full-log and SNAPSHOT-only contexts.","cohort":["G3","G4"],"criteria":["G4"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["e622 Scope OUT: 'guessing historical local channels, mutating old events, treating Jira binding as creation, SNAPSHOT-only legacy inference, compaction, and new filtering/reporting surfaces.'","568c What: 'After process_snapshot restores compiled_state, call _project_legacy_creation_channel(state), the state-shaped helper supplied by e622.'","e622 test coverage: tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/mutate/test_creation_channel.py -k legacy_positive/legacy_negative — full-log tests only, no SNAPSHOT-path variant.","568c AC3 tests the SNAPSHOT path (test_reducer_snapshot.py -k creation_channel) but exercises the helper as a black box imported from e622 without e622 owning that test scenario.","container pairing: parent + 568c-b44b-7e2b-4d87/6fe2-ab22-c231-4a41/e622-a596-3ceb-4f74"],"finding":"Child e622 explicitly scopes OUT 'SNAPSHOT-only legacy inference' but child 568c's design requires calling _project_legacy_creation_channel (defined and tested only for full-log context in e622) post-process_snapshot for exactly that purpose, creating a conflicting assumption: the helper's correctness in the SNAPSHOT-only inference path is never tested within e622, and 568c treats it as a black box, meaning SNAPSHOT-specific edge cases (e.g., compiled_state that contains creation_channel=None explicitly set versus key absent) may not be exercised anywhere.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f93e31cff56750e4d","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"child e622-a596-3ceb-4f74 (Scope OUT: 'SNAPSHOT-only legacy inference') vs child 568c-b44b-7e2b-4d87 (What: 'After process_snapshot restores compiled_state, call _project_legacy_creation_channel')","norm_id":"n787d218051dfefae","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["A pre-feature SNAPSHOT compiled_state has creation_channel key explicitly set to None (e.g., written by partial tooling) — full-log inference skips this (key present), but SNAPSHOT restore will have state['creation_channel']=None, and the helper's no-op condition (state already has creation_channel) fires, leaving None rather than inferring — a gap not tested by either child.","A SNAPSHOT written by a partially-deployed new binary carries an unexpected creation_channel value; the helper's no-op does not validate it — no test covers this in either child."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Remove 'SNAPSHOT-only legacy inference' from e622's Scope OUT (since the helper it defines is explicitly designed for both contexts per its What section description) and add at least one SNAPSHOT-path edge-case test in e622 or transfer ownership of that edge case to 568c with an explicit AC bullet.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Assign explicit ownership of the 'distinction from actor/environment/source_* provenance' documentation sub-requirement to one child (most naturally 6fe2 as the foundational story) and add a specific documentation AC or file-impact note for it.","cohort":["G3","G4"],"criteria":["G3"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Parent AC11: 'docs/event-schema.md plus docs/output-schemas.md define CREATE/SNAPSHOT placement, the enum, Jira inference, import semantics, plus the distinction from actor/environment/source_* provenance.'","6fe2 Files docs/event-schema.md: 'CREATE channel contract'; docs/output-schemas.md: 'public output semantics' — no mention of actor/environment/source_* distinction.","e622 Files docs/event-schema.md: 'Jira/import channel semantics'; docs/output-schemas.md: 'document Jira/import channel output semantics' — no mention of actor/environment/source_* distinction.","568c Files docs/event-schema.md: 'SNAPSHOT provenance placement'; docs/output-schemas.md: 'document full-log, SNAPSHOT-only, and rebuilt-SNAPSHOT output parity' — no mention of actor/environment/source_* distinction.","Parent success criterion: 'The public schema and documentation define the vocabulary, default/fallback semantics, import behavior, and diagnostic trust boundary.'","container pairing: parent + 568c-b44b-7e2b-4d87/6fe2-ab22-c231-4a41/e622-a596-3ceb-4f74"],"finding":"Parent AC11 requires docs/event-schema.md and docs/output-schemas.md to define 'the distinction from actor/environment/source_* provenance,' but no child explicitly claims to write or test this specific documentation sub-requirement — each child's documentation scope covers only its own channel subset (local, Jira/import, or compaction), leaving the comparative provenance distinction potentially absent from the delivered docs.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fa3af774bc2d9ffc0","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"parent AC11 vs children 6fe2/e622/568c documentation scopes","norm_id":"n6f41dec685e1e2bf","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["All three children deliver their documentation slices, but the final docs/event-schema.md never explicitly states how creation_channel differs from author, env_id, source_author, source_env — an auditor reading the docs cannot distinguish the dimensions.","The test_schema_coverage.py tests lint the doc format but do not assert that the actor/environment/source_* distinction paragraph exists."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Add to 6fe2's docs/event-schema.md task: 'Add a paragraph explicitly contrasting creation_channel with actor (author), environment (env_id), and source_* import fields to satisfy parent AC11 documentation requirement.'","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Designate 568c as the final documentation integration story and add an explicit AC or verification step asserting that the union of all three doc slices satisfies the complete parent AC11 documentation checklist (enum, Jira inference, import semantics, SNAPSHOT placement, actor/env/source_* distinction).","cohort":["G3","G4"],"criteria":["G4"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["6fe2 AC6 prove command includes test_schema_coverage.py — coverage at the time 6fe2 lands will be partial (Jira/import/SNAPSHOT sections not yet written).","e622 AC8 prove command includes test_schema_coverage.py — coverage at the time e622 lands will still miss compaction/SNAPSHOT sections.","568c AC7 prove command includes test_schema_coverage.py — first time full coverage could pass.","No child designates itself as the 'final documentation integration owner' responsible for holistic coverage.","test_schema_coverage.py is used as a gate in all three stories, but it cannot flag missing sections that have not yet been defined as required.","container pairing: parent + 568c-b44b-7e2b-4d87/6fe2-ab22-c231-4a41/e622-a596-3ceb-4f74"],"finding":"The three children collectively fragment documentation of docs/event-schema.md, docs/output-schemas.md, and docs/concurrency.md across all three stories with no designated final-documentation owner, creating a partial-without-remainder risk: each child writes its slice in isolation, but the full cross-cutting picture (enum + Jira inference + import + SNAPSHOT placement + downgrade matrix) only emerges when all three slices are merged — a reviewer for any individual child story cannot verify completeness.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f6b70803ddef426ae","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"child 6fe2-ab22-c231-4a41 (Files: docs/event-schema.md, docs/output-schemas.md), child e622-a596-3ceb-4f74 (Files: docs/event-schema.md, docs/cli-reference.md, docs/output-schemas.md), child 568c-b44b-7e2b-4d87 (Files: docs/event-schema.md, docs/concurrency.md, docs/output-schemas.md)","norm_id":"n9b544155963cc2e9","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["6fe2's test_schema_coverage.py pass does not guarantee e622's Jira/import sections are present — the coverage test only validates what is already defined as required.","A merge of 6fe2 followed by stalled e622 leaves output-schemas.md without Jira/import semantics, passing all 6fe2 gates but violating the parent's AC6 prove command which runs both test_schema_outputs.py and test_schema_coverage.py."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Add to 568c's AC7 prove command a documentation completeness smoke test (e.g., grep assertions for the actor/environment/source_* distinction paragraph in docs/event-schema.md) so the final story landing validates the holistic parent doc requirement.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add a dedicated test in tests/interfaces/store/test_fsck_snapshot_checks.py (or a separate -k flag in the compaction test) that asserts fsck *without* --repair-snapshots reports the new inconsistency for an old-style SNAPSHOT whose retained CREATE carries creation_channel.","cohort":["G3","G4"],"criteria":["G3"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["568c What: 'src/rebar/_commands/fsck.py: detect an old-style SNAPSHOT missing recorded provenance when a retained CREATE carries it and route --repair-snapshots through the existing rebuild seam.'","568c AC5: 'A simulated old-style SNAPSHOT missing creation_channel is detected and repaired from its retained CREATE through the existing fsck --repair-snapshots seam. Prove with uv run pytest -q tests/interfaces/lifecycle/test_creation_channel_compaction.py -k \"rebuild or horizon or rollback_recovery\" tests/integration/test_concurrency_regression.py.'","The -k 'rebuild or horizon or rollback_recovery' filter bundles detection and repair into a single assertion; no separate test verifies that fsck returns a non-zero exit or specific detection output before --repair-snapshots is invoked.","Existing tests/interfaces/store/test_fsck_snapshot_checks.py is listed only as a regression guard (AC6), not expanded for the new detection case.","container pairing: parent + 568c-b44b-7e2b-4d87/6fe2-ab22-c231-4a41/e622-a596-3ceb-4f74"],"finding":"Child 568c adds fsck.py detection of old-style SNAPSHOTs missing recorded provenance (when a retained CREATE carries it) and routes --repair-snapshots through the existing rebuild seam, but no child AC provides a dedicated test that independently exercises the fsck *detection* step (SNAPSHOT_INCONSISTENT flagging for this new condition) separately from the repair step — the rollback_recovery marker in 568c AC5 bundles detection and repair together.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f10024d546e1dcb5c","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"child 568c-b44b-7e2b-4d87 AC5 and Files (src/rebar/_commands/fsck.py)","norm_id":"n34e65b06df5bb11d","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["fsck detects the new condition but silently drops it (e.g., by not adding a new check-kind) while --repair-snapshots still works; the bundled test passes because repair works, masking the detection gap.","A future refactor removes the new fsck detection code path while the repair path remains working; no test fails."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Split 568c AC5 into two sub-assertions: (a) fsck without --repair-snapshots returns a non-zero exit / specific output when an old-style SNAPSHOT lacks creation_channel but the retained CREATE carries it; (b) fsck --repair-snapshots resolves the inconsistency. Add (a) to tests/interfaces/store/test_fsck_snapshot_checks.py.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["T4"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":[],"finding":"The rollback plan is purely preventive — it tells operators to stop `rebar compact` before downgrading — but provides no restorative path if an operator runs compaction on the old binary anyway. The T4 criterion requires an explicit rollback/back-out plan, not just a preventive warning; once the bad compaction occurs, creation_channel is silently and permanently lost from affected tickets with no described recovery.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f5fed8d2a4cd03ac0","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Architecture Decisions — 'Compaction preserves creation_channel' paragraph and Risks and Mitigations — 'Snapshot data loss' bullet; AC item for docs/concurrency.md","norm_id":"n6869a18261acc559","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":[],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Extend the downgrade section to require: (1) before switching binaries, record the set of ticket IDs that have been compacted (SNAPSHOT present) under the new binary so they are known to carry creation_channel; (2) if old-binary compaction is detected post-hoc (e.g., via a SNAPSHOT missing creation_channel), define recovery as: upgrade to new binary, run `rebar rebuild-snapshot` (or equivalent) on the affected ticket IDs to regenerate creation_channel from the raw CREATE event. Add this to docs/concurrency.md and gate it with a test.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["G3","G4"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":[],"finding":"Child 6fe2's AC2 covers only 'MCP create_ticket, create_idea, and first-use log_session' for the mcp channel, but the parent AC1 requires 'identities' to also report the invoking interface (mcp) for MCP creation. The MCP create_identity tool in _mcp_writes.py calls rebar.create_identity → _identity.create_identity_core, but the threading mechanism from the MCP boundary through the library facade to create_identity_core is not specified in 6fe2, and the AC does not name MCP identity creation as a covered case.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f465c5470ad8b1ecc","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"child 6fe2-ab22-c231-4a41 — Acceptance Criteria AC2 and Scope/Files sections","norm_id":"nd5a97cd5f5ec003a","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":[],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"In 6fe2, either (a) add a creation_channel parameter to rebar.create_identity in _lib_writes.py and thread mcp from _mcp_writes.py, or (b) add a test case for MCP create_identity to the -k mcp test and confirm the threading mechanism in the What/Files sections. Add 'MCP create_identity' explicitly to 6fe2 AC2.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["T12"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":[],"finding":"The rollback three-state schema matrix is documented in prose but no AC tests the actual downgrade path — specifically that an old binary reading new-code SNAPSHOTs, new CREATE events, or never-compacted tickets behaves as specified.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f8024563847e5545a","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Architecture Decisions — rollback matrix; Acceptance Criteria — compaction ACs","norm_id":"n571174785daa1b95","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":[],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["E3"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":[],"finding":"The plan claims `creation_channel` is 'immutable' in the title and Architecture Decisions, but provides no enforcement mechanism or test that rejects a subsequent event attempting to overwrite the field on an existing ticket.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f7a14f7ffb125980a","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Title: 'Track immutable ticket creation channel'; Architecture Decisions — 'Add creation_channel to CREATE data and compiled ticket state'","norm_id":"n920650fe69f0d088","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":[],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"In the reducer's compiled_state projection logic, treat creation_channel as a CREATE-only field: set it once from the first CREATE event and ignore it on all subsequent events. Add a corresponding test: `pytest -q tests/unit/reducer/test_creation_channel_immutability.py -k 'mutation_cannot_overwrite'`.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.6,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["G6"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":[],"finding":"The plan states 'The shared core carries and validates the declared internal value' (Architecture Decisions), implying CREATE-time enum validation applies to all channels including 'jira'. However, the Jira inbound creation path in apply_inbound_records.py calls _write_event_file directly, bypassing create_core entirely — so the channel value written to Jira-originated CREATE events never passes through the proposed validator in create_core. If a future maintainer adds a new Jira inbound writer or mistypes the literal 'jira', no writer-side guard catches it.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f870cf049b247bf83","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Architecture Decisions — 'The shared core carries and validates the declared internal value'; also src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/apply_inbound_records.py:_inbound_create_write_create_event (line 125, create_data dict)","norm_id":"n0fd761d92706a3f5","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":[],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Add one sentence to Architecture Decisions: 'The inbound Jira materialization path sets creation_channel directly in CREATE data and does not route through create_core; a module-level assertion or constant reference in apply_inbound_records.py pins the vocabulary for that path.'","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null}],"impact_model_version":"plan-v3","material_fingerprint":"4134d2c4ab5564be","metrics":{"claim_path":"no-llm/no-network (structural; the fast claim check is a local HMAC verify)","det_ms":312.9,"llm_calls":22,"llm_ms":954846.5,"total_ms":955286.2,"verify_requests":46},"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","regver":"b293b9a55de591cc","runner":"pydantic_ai","schema":"plan_review_result_v2","ticket_id":"jira-reb-977","ticket_type":"epic","verdict":"INDETERMINATE","verified_at_sha":"8bb261c19e933b5705a14c0625e9919e0d53634a"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"REVIEW_RESULT","timestamp":1784265610938681001,"uuid":"07599e91-317a-4f21-9ee6-3ebf9b974ebe"}